pullRequest.body:
Define auxiliary polynomials for the secant-and-tangent negation `neg` and addition `add` on `Fin 3 -> F`. Note that the group operations are defined from scratch instead of pulling back the group operations from the affine case, as this will be more convenient for rewriting and allows them to be defined over a ring. I don't see an easy way to define an analogous `slope` function as in `Affine` when there are now `Z`-coordinates in the polynomials.

This is the second in a series of four PRs leading to #9405 and is analogous to #9417

How is `u â€¢ Q` not definitionally equal to `![uÂ² * Q x, uÂ³ * Q y, u * Q z]`? The proof of `smul_fin3` is `rfl`.
Whoops, I meant syntactically equal!
Why is this private? You're guaranteeing that nobody else will ever need this?
Ditto.
(for anyone else reading this: the answer is "there's a better lemma later")
What about `negDblY`?
This sounds like a good idea. We'd have to change the `Affine` versions too.
this could have been `negAddY` . I think I far prefer my suggestions to just "add a ' to indicate a negation" -- usually adding a ' indicates a variant, not a completely different function.
Ditto
Is there a reason you're avoiding `ring`? Is `ring1` faster or better in some way?

I know that in Lean 3 `ring` tries `ring1`, and if it fails it applies `ring_nf`. I only have terminal `ring`s, so I prefer to get notified when it fails, rather than waiting a long time for `ring_nf` to normalise and ultimately fail to close the goal.
Again what is the logic of all these `private` lemmas?
These are auxiliary lemmas for `toAffine_add/dblX/Y_of_eq`, which are essentially the same lemma but with an actual sane expression on the right hand side that is useful.
`negAddY`?
Ditto

You might want to make the remark that this definition is not mathematically sensible if R isn't a field (even though it compiles). I think that in the non-field case the correct definition is probably that the ideal generated by the three evals is all of R. Otherwise you can specialise at a maximal ideal containing the ideal generated by the evals and get a singular specialization.

So it's *not* the Y-coordinate! Would it be better to say something like "the Y coordinate of the 3rd point of intersection of the tangent line at P with the curve. In other words, the Y coordinate of -2P."?
Same comment as above. It's the Y coordinate of the third point of intersection, i.e. of -(P+Q).
